# Ask Aunt Lurlene (Python / Flask)

An anonymous Southern advice column built like a modern vintage newspaper.
Readers submit anonymously; Aunt Lurlene logs in, gets breaking-news popups,
and publishes answers that **everyone** then sees.

This is a single-file Python app. The entire web page is embedded inside
`app.py` and served by Flask, so there is **no standalone HTML file** sitting in
the repo — which is exactly why this version deploys cleanly on Railway. Railway
sees `requirements.txt`, runs the Python program, and the program serves the
page. It cannot fall back to "just hosting static files."

## Files (only two matter)
| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `app.py` | The whole app: server, database, and the embedded web page |
| `requirements.txt` | Python dependencies (this is what makes Railway run Python) |

`requirements.txt` must contain ONLY these two lines and nothing else:

```
Flask==3.0.3
psycopg2-binary==2.9.9
```

There is no Procfile and no gunicorn. Railway detects Python and runs
`python app.py` automatically.

Admin login (change for production): **username `angie` / password `password123`**

## Storage
- With a PostgreSQL database attached (Railway injects `DATABASE_URL`): all
  answers are shared by every visitor and survive redeploys.
- With no database: the app still boots using a local SQLite file so you can
  test immediately. (On Railway, add PostgreSQL for real shared storage — the
  local file is temporary and not shared.)

